data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>The Arlington County Board plans to vote Saturday afternoon on giving Amazon $23 million and other incentives to build a headquarters campus in Crystal City, but only after hearing scores of northern Virginia residents and advocates testify for or against the project.
The five-member board held public hearings first during its regular meeting Friday morning, and then at a special meeting Friday afternoon. The spectacle lasted more than nine hours and included close to 500 speakers, all calling out against the project or supporting the plans to lease the county’s land in Crystal City to Amazon for $23 million. But speakers also listed an array of suggestions for adding accountability measures to the planned incentives and limiting the scope of the impact that Amazon’s move could have on affordable housing in the area.
The board begins voting at 2 p.m. Saturday on an agenda that includes authorizing the county manager to negotiate an incentive for Amazon to build its regional headquarters in the Crystal City-Arlington East Falls Church neighborhoods.
The proposed loan agreement between the county and the JBG Smith/Amazon partnership would provide $23 million to reimburse costs the developer incurs in connection with the construction of the project. The agreement would also impose deed restrictions on the property, running through 2050, which would block the property from being redeveloped or sold unless it continues to house Amazon HQ2. Under the deed restrictions, the parcel going to Amazon would continue to be leased to the company for $300 a year through 2034 and would then turn into an ownership agreement at no cost.
The proposed restrictions would also allow for JBG Smith or its successors to sell the property at fair market value if needed during the terms, but disagreements between the county and the developer would have to be settled in a nearby Circuit Court.
Much like the recent public hearing on the Pantages entertainment center in Fairfax City, the drawn-out meeting in Arlington saw residents and activists lining up to both air grievances about the concentration of wealth Amazon would have over the Washington, D.C., area and express their approval of the plans.
“This fall I experienced firsthand the impact of the housing crisis when my new friend Linda Mills, a 90-year-old woman, died of hypothermia in her home,” said Arlington resident Mary Norton. “When I read everything I could about Amazon’s plans and saw how much space they will occupy, I made the connection. We are not providing far better homes for far too many Arlington residents. There are thousands… living in the verge of homelessness and there is nothing in Amazon’s plans to address this.”
On the other hand, former state Sen. Richard H. Black, R-West Point, of Arlington spoke in defense of the changes the city would see.

Tom Frieden, the director of the CDC, said that even though officials were confident that the Dallas man infected four others where the first case of Ebola to be diagnosed in this country, it is possible others were exposed.
During an appearance on CNN, Frieden noted that three people had tested negative for the disease so far, but the results could be incomplete.
"Most patients show some sort of symptoms between three and 21 days, so we have 21 days on the clock as there are other colleagues who have a higher probability of transmission who aren't showing symptoms so far," Frieden said.
Officials identified those four "probable" contacts and sequestered them as a precaution; the first of the contacts quarantined has been released. An official at the CDC said that the numbers could "go up at this point," and that the people being monitored by the CDC could total in the dozens. Epidemiologists who study infectious diseases, however, said they expected that the number of suspected contacts -- those who were in direct contact with the men for a substantial time -- to be in the tens, or at most the low twenties.
In Dallas, the two other people exposed to the Ebola virus tested negative for the disease Sunday, CBS reported. A decorated muay Thai practitioner, Alexandre began his mixed martial arts career in 1999, when he scored a knockout victory in his professional debut. “He will be a great addition to our already deep roster of world class mixed martial arts competitors and a huge draw for fans of World Series of Fighting in all corners of the globe.”
While Alexandre’s has seen the brightest moments of his career in his native Brazil -- including five championship victories and two to three successful title defenses -- he moved to compete in other prominent promotions to bring his abilities to a global audience.
“I am excited to be making my extremely anticipated debut for World Series of Fighting and look forward to coming home with the world championship belt,” Alexandre stated. “I am excited to begin my training camp with a quality team and to fight again as soon as possible.”

The 78-page document (by an Obama appointee, no less) concludes that Clinton’s server and email practices as secretary of state were “not an appropriate method” for handling classified information, and that Clinton did not actively work to wrap up her private server and turn over all of her emails this past summer, prefering instead to have State Department lawyers work through the process for her. It accuses her staff of dragging out the process so as not to risk damaging her candidacy.
She tried to escape accountability for her actions and mishandling of classified information, wrote Bill Miller, the IG’s staff director for management and inspector general. Miller cites Clinton’s “extensive and continual attempts to receive and retain classified information” and concludes that she and senior staff “were not candid” about what was on her personal server. He gives numerous examples of how poorly classified information was handled. It also points out that Clinton did not provide her BlackBerry to the IT specialists in the eight months she was secretary.
The report also confirms she only handed over a small fraction of the content of her emails to the State Department. At the heart of its recommendation to cover all emails sent and received is the conclusion that Clinton’s staff used private email accounts ending in @clintonemail.com before she did, thus setting the bureaucratic ball in motion that led to her server. This dramatically contradicts the public statements Clinton made last March.
“I opted for convenience to use my personal email account, which was allowed by the State Department,” Clinton said. And again in June, “I did not email any classified material to anyone on my email. There is no classified material. So I’m certainly well aware of the classification requirements and did not send classified material.”
That is a gross distortion of what happened. Clinton’s staff sent classified material to Clinton repeatedly, and Clinton called classified material that she knew was sensitive “secret” in interviews with the FBI.

<|begin_of_text|>Thorpe of the New York Trucking and Delivery Association says the decision to raise penalties won’t solve the parking crisis.
For more than a decade, Ken Thorpe has been a soldier in the fight against parking tickets, which has become part of his job description as manager at the New York Trucking and Delivery Association.
He has spent countless hours in court where the fines for failing to abide by parking rules have grown to questionable levels. He has given up on the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey after it outfitted cars with surveillance cameras that record driver activity and send ticket warnings.
He tried to escape to the New Jersey and Connecticut Turnpikes, where drivers must have an E-ZPass, but even there there are problems for his New York-licensed semitrailer trucks.
Thorpe managed to master the most contentious parking ticket nexus of all for the city, 104th Street west of Dyer Avenue on the west side of Manhattan. That intersection, Thorpe says, breeds a congestion situation that triggers automated ticket-writing machines. Truckers don’t have the option to pay for space, as do other drivers, and instead must walk the block to find a metered spot or go out on First Street to use the U.S. Postal Service lot.
Others on 104th Street are not pleased. They say the truck parking rules indiscriminately pick on semitrailers and other trucks, which supposedly are not allowed west of Ninth Avenue in favor of designated truck ways. The ban doesn’t apply to Postal Service vans — so long as they are using Postal Service lots. Monday, the lack of simplicity angered a bunch of bicycle commuters.
Early morning drivers parked their bikes on the north side of 104th Street, where trucks like Thorpe's are prohibited from parking from 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. Monday morning, Thorpe walked into a buzzing intersection of gesticulating bicyclists, locked bikes and one spitting truck who had already parked on the digital camera-monitored side of the street and circled the block trying to find a spot before he was double-parked.
Thorpe has faced these parking inspectors since the day he started the job 11 years ago. He used to get 12 tickets per day for parking near the building he manages for the trucking group. The last two years, after lobbyists, strategists and Thorpe fought a parking war for compliance, he has been reduced to one ticket per day to 400 per month. Many of Thorpe’s members have mailing addresses in cities like Chicago, Atlanta, Philadelphia and Boston, complicating automated ticket enforcement. Thorpe’s towing comes from inside New York and those 400 tickets typically end up in the mail.

<|begin_of_text|>Posted on Wed, Mar 14, 2012 : 8:40 a.m.
A Manchester woman’s selfless gift could help extend the life of a co-worker’s husband, WXYZ reports.
Lisa Moutinho, an administrator at ProMedica, told the TV station that she put her hands in milk for two minutes after she heard about the need for platelets to treat firefighters hurt in a Quebec tragedy. Platelets are used to treat heart attacks, blunt force trauma and shock. Moutinho’s platelets were used to save four firefighters injured in a tanker explosion near Lac-Megantic Quebec, where a train carrying crude oil derailed into dozens of homes, leading to explosions and fires there. Five people were killed, and 35 are still missing.

<|begin_of_text|>For a career that once seemed so good on paper, the crisis in teacher recruitment is now hardly ever out of the news.
There are not enough people signing up to become teachers and too many are dropping out - some experienced due to the stress and tough managerial approach of schools. Nearly all commentators agree that teacher retention is a serious issue.
On Radio 4's Today programme this week, John Coldwell, a teacher in Cambridge, described leaving the profession after being ignored, when he raised the need for changes in his school that would improve student behaviour. But perhaps more concerning is his description of other teachers who have stayed in the profession and why: "They probably felt that they had too much invested in their lives in terms of property and children".
This raises the interesting question of what government programmes or incentives are in place to support teachers' well-being?
### Sticking in there
There is growing evidence of the effect that stress has on teachers' personal lives and their reluctance to continue working under these pressures. A recent survey suggests that UK teachers are more stressed than most other jobs in the country.
So what are the resources available to support teachers' well-being?
In 2002, the DfES announced a pilot Professional Leadership Plan which supported 200 middle to senior managers on a personalised career development programme. This was extended for the 2003-2005 cycle before being superseded by two other funded programmes, National Leaders of Education (NLEs) and Programme Managers of Inclusive Schools (PMIS).
NLEs are now supported by other flagship schemes, including the National College for School Leadership (NCSL), and Local Authority Challenge Partners (a CPD network to develop partnership working between local authorities and School Improvement Partners).
Teachers' well-being is considered by NCSL to lie _within leadership_'.
Although these initiatives are now growing in number and strength, the people that feel they need these types of support are not necessarily those who are able to access it. For example, NLEs have to be nominated by a headteacher. Senior middle managers may go through their careers without encountering or accessing these resources. Newer, struggling heads often do not have the networks or contacts to be nominated for NLE or PMIS training.
### Retaining teachers and attracting more
So how is it possible to retain teachers, while attracting more to a profession that is increasingly fraught with stress and problems?
Increasingly, support groups are being set up and they are encouraging large numbers of teachers to take off their national badge or have mailing forums.

The small things you do to lower costs and increase output can be the difference between a failing business and soaring profits. No matter how good your team members are, you can bet that there is at least one inefficiency slowing your progress. You can use your daily observations to uncover where the slowdowns are and eliminate them.
In this article, you will learn about 17 places to look for inefficiencies in the workplace. We will also share 7 ways to improve workplace efficiency.
Where to Look for Inefficiencies
Your daily tasks can uncover a lot of areas where your business wastes money and time. To optimize efficiency, check your operating expenses, travel expenses, accounts payable, production numbers, office expenses, and charitable contributions. The steps below allow you to examine all of them and improve your company’s bottom line.
#1 –  Compare Employee Salaries to Timecard Costs
Comparing salary expenses to timecard costs is an important part of gauging efficiency. Timecards refer to the time it takes to do a job. Keeping good records helps you establish payroll numbers which are accurate. Comparing payroll to the total number of hours recorded on employee timecards for a certain period allows you to accurately determine productivity.
To get the most out of examining timecard info, you need to use a timekeeping system rather than hand-written sheets. This makes it easy to see how much time each individual employee took on any given activity.
Using a report management system for your business is an excellent idea. With reports, you can generate insights from data collected and recorded by your employees directly. Businesses that record accurate timecards get optimal efficiency because they have a clear picture of how much time each worker puts in on any given project. It helps you ensure they get the credit they deserve for their additional efforts without resorting to manual entry.
Once you know how much time each employee should spend on specific projects, it’s easier to determine the number of hours they work. The timecard report also shows you which employees are more productive than others. Comparing productivity levels among employees will significantly increase company efficiency. It can lead to a better understanding of why some people are more valuable than others.
Inefficiencies lead to frustration among employees. That’s why you should make your reports as helpful to employees as possible. Since your timecards cover several employees’ hours, you can use the data to get better insights into who is making the most money off your business. Use this information to give each team member an incentive to do more.
Your company should also use calendars to monitor employee productivity changes. With an easy-to-access calendar, you can see how long it takes each team

<|begin_of_text|>NEW YORK (AP) — Could the U.S. lose its top credit rating even if a deal is reached to raise the debt limit?
Market analysts and investors increasingly say yes. The outcome won't be quite as scary as a default, but it would mean lower ratings at the world's biggest credit agency and likely higher financing costs for everything from commercial loans to the sale of money market funds.
"The very real risk is that the downgrade scenario is now blurring the horizon," says Patrick Daoud, managing director with Fitch Ratings, a New York-based rating agency. "This has now become a market concern."
Standard & Poor's upgraded its outlook for the U.S. credit rating Friday, but it was a signal there's still a chance the country could be downgraded, and that it will take a vote of solidarity from Congress to stop it.
Lawmakers on Thursday voted to raise the limit on the debt that the country can borrow, retroactively to May. The U.S. Treasury always borrows and spends more than it collects in taxes, it needs debt approvals to avoid default.
But the bill's passage averted the immediate threat of default for now. It includes an increase in the borrowing limit by around $300 billion through Nov. 18.
A date on when the U.S. can reach its borrowing limits has been extremely hard to pin down in recent weeks because of the uncertainty over whether a deal to raise the borrowing limit would be struck in Congress.
Financial analysts and investors often say a downgrade is inevitable unless a "grand bargain" to significantly reduce long-term deficits and cut the country's debt is reached.
Now, many say Standard & Poor's thinks that's unlikely to happen and it was forced to come to grips with that assumption, which is why it upgraded its outlook to "stable."
"There was some sense from the market that the stakes in this deal — the debt ceiling deal — were so huge that Standard & Poor's would have to raise the rating in some form or another," says Ed Mills, Washington policy analyst at FBR Capital Markets.
Standard & Poor's had upgraded its outlook for the U.S. on July 13, forecasting U.S. leaders could agree on a broad approach in the long-term.
Now, investors seem to believe that's not happening. San Francisco Fed President John Williams made the rounds on TV Sunday, pointing out that if the U.S. approves a debt ceiling increase, it will have the maximum wiggle room to attempt large reductions in its long-term deficit and national debt.
St. Louis Fed President James Bullard, also spoke with CBS News Sunday, noting that S&P's new move changes the status quo for Washington lawmakers.

(This first of two perspectives is by Sharon Bennett, VP Data Management Solutions at EnterpriseDB, while the second by Daniel Peters, CEO of Basking Ridge. Both appear in the February 2016 edition of Embedded Vision #71.)
It’s no secret that data is power. The democratization of data is a real phenomenon happening today.
Companies both large and small are increasingly recognizing and seizing the power that data provides, and data is being used in almost every conceivable way. It is used to enhance experience, to develop understanding, to support decision making and make predictions, to harness sales and marketing efforts, for risk mitigation, or to improve profitability by countless other means.
While the means of the driving technologies may differ, the generations of data workers and credentialed data scientists often use the same methods: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), computational statistics, machine learning, predictive analytics, and perhaps even artificial intelligence. Users graph data on-chip via real-time data services for predictive results, for example.
A lot of things can go wrong when one user infers for tens, or hundreds, or even thousands of users. One data science team can be unproductive when not tied to a culture of executing on real insight. In some cases, a collective data team can be too small for applications where it is essential to scale and extend new horizons in insights.
The challenge is in clear demarcation and balance. The balance varies by application but always requires having a shared set of facts about the data at hand and shared downstream data pipelines. As new applications emerge, drawn from the near limitless field of data enriched by a complex service-oriented world, the emerging phrase of “data democracy” describes data as a shared resource that empowers individuals and organizations to create, access, and use data as directed. Its most powerful application is cross-domain analytics, where specialized models are generated by domain experts and applied across diverse data and models can themselves be applied across diverse domains. Organization wide, this is what many well-informed data scientists are striving for.

<|begin_of_text|>For a career that once seemed so good on paper, the crisis in teacher recruitment is now hardly ever out of the news.
There are not enough people signing up to become teachers and too many are dropping out - some experienced due to the stress and tough managerial approach of schools. Nearly all commentators agree that teacher retention is a serious issue.
On Radio 4's Today programme this week, John Coldwell, a teacher in Cambridge, described leaving the profession after being ignored, when he raised the need for changes in his school that would improve student behaviour. But perhaps more concerning is his description of other teachers who have stayed in the profession and why: "They probably felt that they had too much invested in their lives in terms of property and children".
This raises the interesting question of what government programmes or incentives are in place to support teachers' well-being?
### Sticking in there
There is growing evidence of the effect that stress has on teachers' personal lives and their reluctance to continue working under these pressures. A recent survey suggests that UK teachers are more stressed than most other jobs in the country.
So what are the resources available to support teachers' well-being?
In 2002, the DfES announced a pilot Professional Leadership Plan which supported 200 middle to senior managers on a personalised career development programme. This was extended for the 2003-2005 cycle before being superseded by two other funded programmes, National Leaders of Education (NLEs) and Programme Managers of Inclusive Schools (PMIS).
NLEs are now supported by other flagship schemes, including the National College for School Leadership (NCSL), and Local Authority Challenge Partners (a CPD network to develop partnership working between local authorities and School Improvement Partners).
Teachers' well-being is considered by NCSL to lie _within leadership_'.
Although these initiatives are now growing in number and strength, the people that feel they need these types of support are not necessarily those who are able to access it. For example, NLEs have to be nominated by a headteacher. Senior middle managers may go through their careers without encountering or accessing these resources. Newer, struggling heads often do not have the networks or contacts to be nominated for NLE or PMIS training.
### Retaining teachers and attracting more
So how is it possible to retain teachers, while attracting more to a profession that is increasingly fraught with stress and problems?
Increasingly, support groups are being set up and they are encouraging large numbers of teachers to take off their national badge or have mailing forums.
In the past, teachers have been reluctant to fight for better working environments, thereby keeping new candidates for the profession inside the profession. These new initiatives are anonymous forums that are supporting teaching staff

<|begin_of_text|>Gloria Williams Sander is hoping that her home in Glendale’s North Cumberland Heights neighborhood soon will become a historical district.
With her neighbor Susan Dasso and others, Williams Sander canvassed the neighborhood a few years ago to learn if any residents would be willing to support an inclusionary district, and she reported that unanimous support emerged.
“There was no one against it,” she said.
Williams Sander was among area leaders, including Glendale Mayor Dave Weaver, who were honored for their efforts toward fostering community gardens at a ceremony on Saturday. But perhaps more important to her was being recognized alongside her son Chris Sander, a horticulturist with the city of Glendale, for their enthusiasms in gardening.
“I couldn’t have gotten through this if it weren’t for him,” Williams Sander said.
Another son, Ansley Christopher Sander, horticulturist with the city of Glendale, backed his parents, adding that his work later in life in gardening and horticulture was inspired by his experience growing up near lush garden spaces with his mother and father.
The garden sets a tone for the neighborhood, said officials.
Tim Streets, division chief of Glendale Water & Power, described the growing network of around 100 community gardens on city property as an improvement for Glendale residents.
Beyond the garden, Williams Sander’s house on West Harvard Road has other intriguing features, too, not the least of which is an arched library room featuring insets of windows from a demolished Carnegie Library.
“Back in 1960, you couldn’t have gotten $150 for that,” she said during a tour, pointing upward to the restored windows.
From NASA to Looney Tunes, Williams Sander’s history with the house is colorful and detailed down to the NASA history books inside the circular sunroom adorned with NASA-themed objects.
Williams Sander was a Bedford resident when she married Garry Sander, who was a NASA aerospace engineer and their family moved to Glendale in 1962, she said.
“Garry loved it here because it was rural,” she said.
Even after they settled down on West Harvard, there were more moves to other Glendale addresses when Williams Sander began work as a civil leader for the city.
Not long after he started with NASA, the EPA made advances, Williams Sander said. The space agency’s Apollo missions ended a year after Sander took his final trip to NASA, and he went to work for Bell Telephone Laboratory, then IBM and finally returned to NASA via Hughes Aircraft.
Garry Sander died in 2006, of Parkinson’s disease.
The garden changes fortunes for inside spaces in the house, too, Williams Sander said.

The fragile political and social environment could prove a hurdle for 76-year-old President Roch Racine's quest for re-election on Nov. 19.

Violence has rocked Guinea since 2011, when a segment of the military briefly seized power. Anti-September coup anger seethed last year as the economy spiraled down thanks to falling commodity prices.

data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>As many British visitors to France have learnt to their dismay, if you ask a local, “Parlez-vous anglais?”, the answer is often “Non”.
Such a response, perhaps accompanied by a dismissive Gallic shrug, may prompt you to reach first for your phrase book, then for your map to ascertain where the nearest English-speaking establishment might be. None of which is conducive to exploring the real France, for prefering directed to destinations blazoned with symbols of international commerce rather than able to dissociate yourself from the crowd and experience some of the myriad discoveries that await.
Not that all France ’s charms are universally obvious. For some, Normandy ’s seascapes of elegant fishing boats never vary, as much as the country’s culinary appeal may be endlessly,tantalizing. But then, mix these with the abrupt realization that if you don’t speak French when ordering lunch for yourself and family, you won’t get exactly what you want, nor especially what you paid for.
There’s another problem associated with communications. Closely linked with the previously mentioned dissatisfaction is the tendency to generalise and categorise aspects of French life experience to the point where, having spent just one visit to somewhere, Paris for example, you really do think you have the city by the horns.
Yet to the minds of the Parisiens, associations going back in time literally hundreds of years help make up the fabric of their lives. Paris is so subtly dramatically beautiful in every direction that its joie de vivre is a joy to behold. By this it is not suggested that you have to be able to utter a sentence in French in order to enjoy the city. But to be able to get a little closer to what a place is all about, to talk to people about their experience, to hear what goes on – well, the conversation really would be worthwhile.
Be warned though, conversation in any language is really only half the message. Like it or not, where visual stimuli are the glass to the wine of France ’s charms, French is the cork.

<|begin_of_text|>Thorpe of the New York Trucking and Delivery Association says the decision to raise penalties won’t solve the parking crisis.
For more than a decade, Ken Thorpe has been a soldier in the fight against parking tickets, which has become part of his job description as manager at the New York Trucking and Delivery Association.
He has spent countless hours in court where the fines for failing to abide by parking rules have grown to questionable levels. He has given up on the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey after it outfitted cars with surveillance cameras that record driver activity and send ticket warnings.
He tried to escape to the New Jersey and Connecticut Turnpikes, where drivers must have an E-ZPass, but even there there are problems for his New York-licensed semitrailer trucks.
Thorpe managed to master the most contentious parking ticket nexus of all for the city, 104th Street west of Dyer Avenue on the west side of Manhattan. That intersection, Thorpe says, breeds a congestion situation that triggers automated ticket-writing machines. Truckers don’t have the option to pay for space, as do other drivers, and instead must walk the block to find a metered spot or go out on First Street to use the U.S. Postal Service lot.
Others on 104th Street are not pleased. They say the truck parking rules indiscriminately pick on semitrailers and other trucks, which supposedly are not allowed west of Ninth Avenue in favor of designated truck ways. The ban doesn’t apply to Postal Service vans — so long as they are using Postal Service lots. Monday, the lack of simplicity angered a bunch of bicycle commuters.
Early morning drivers parked their bikes on the north side of 104th Street, where trucks like Thorpe's are prohibited from parking from 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. Monday morning, Thorpe walked into a buzzing intersection of gesticulating bicyclists, locked bikes and one spitting truck who had already parked on the digital camera-monitored side of the street and circled the block trying to find a spot before he was double-parked.
Thorpe has faced these parking inspectors since the day he started the job 11 years ago. He used to get 12 tickets per day for parking near the building he manages for the trucking group. The last two years, after lobbyists, strategists and Thorpe fought a parking war for compliance, he has been reduced to one ticket per day to 400 per month. Many of Thorpe’s members have mailing addresses in cities like Chicago, Atlanta, Philadelphia and Boston, complicating automated ticket enforcement. Thorpe’s towing comes from inside New York and those 400 tickets typically end up in the mail.

Angelo “Andy” Douglas Azzato, 47, of Lucerne Valley, was found at about 9:30 a.m. in the eastbound lanes of Old Woman Springs Road east of Cypress Street, close to the San Bernardino County line, said Cal Fire Battalion Chief Rob Fuemmeler.
Azzato’s bicycle was on the westbound side of the road, Fuemmeler said.
A 911 caller reported around 8:40 a.m. finding someone on the ground in Old Woman Springs Road, according to a spokesperson with California Highway Patrol dispatch.
According to Fuemmeler, Azzato died at the scene of a single-vehicle collision.
“Law enforcement determined that it was a hit-and-run,” Fuemmeler said.
Old Woman Springs Road was closed between Joshua Avenue and Ridge Crest Drive as fire and law enforcement personnel arrived at the scene, the Cal Fire chief said.
Investigators were trying to locate the vehicle and driver who struck Azzato.

Record-breaking warm waters along Australia's northeast coast during 2014-15 laid waste to some sections of the reef, with the spectacle Australia's worst ever mass bleaching event.
In this year's first major climate-related event to blight the reef, ocean temperatures have again climbed toward record highs, leaving coral communities across the Great Barrier Reef extremely susceptible to a repeat.
Coral bleaching happens when fragile polyps -- the microscopic animals that form the building blocks of coral colonies -- abandon their symbiotic relationship with microscopic algae called zooxanthellae, which tone, colour and provide energy to the coral.
Bleaching only occurs if conditions become too hot for nature's partners to work together -- often due to hot weather.
When coral colonies lose their zooxanthellae, they are left ghostly white in appearance, and without their symbiotic supply of nutrition they decline and die.
Dr James Kerry, a coral scientist at the reef's Australian Institute of Marine Science, said even the Coral Sea escaped the hot blob of water which migrated from Australia's continental shelf each summer.
"Ninety per cent of the time, climatic conditions in the reef's offshore waters help protect coral communities," he said.
Mr Kerry said warm seas dramatically increased water temperatures, which bleached the fringing reef's corals and facilitated bacterial and other pathogens, causing coral deaths.
"The reefs are deteriorating more rapidly this year compared with last year because ocean temperatures have been record warm," he said.
"Coral just can't compete with bacteria; they simply eat it and that's bleeding coral to death."
Mr Kerry said the marine environment near Rockhampton in Central Queensland -- a major shipwrecking area on the Great Barrier Reef -- was already recording unusually high numbers of bleached coral communities.
"If you look at the damage already recorded in the central and southern sectors of the Great Barrier Reef, it is worse than last year," he said.
"Rockhampton is 1,000 kilometres north and already there's lots of coral being affected well prior to November and December, when it's normally at its warmest.
Mr Kerry said in 2016, reefs in far northern waters off Lizard Island were prone to bleaching and death, and if there were large numbers of coral colonies bleached in territories north of latitude 19 degrees southerly latitude, reefs in southern territories like Cairns would also succumb.

<|begin_of_text|>It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions. You can minimize distractions from competitors, hecklers at cross-country meets or even your own internal doubts by developing your focus.
Why Do I Need to Stay Focused?
While many people run for the exercise, fun and social aspects of the sport, when you are competing in races or devoted to improving your time, it is important to stay focused. Being focused has a direct correlation with your performance. When you stay focused, you can probably improve your time by kilometers per day because you aren't as scatterbrained during your run.
How to Stay Focused
While keeping focused depends on the individual, there are a few things you do to keep your mental game on point.
Visualize a Strong Performance
Visualize what you want to happen. Don't think about scenarios that are going to sideline you. Don't think about a time that you had a lackluster performance. You want to visualize yourself running strong and well. Focus on the way you want to feel when you finish the run. Once you solidify this image in your mind, you won't think of anything else except the way you want to feel at the end of your run.
Prepare Mentally
Some people like to listen to music while running. Choosing a genre that supports your motivation can keep your running buzz going. Certain playlists can help you achieve your goals -- or prevent you from self-sabotaging yourself. The playlist could be music by upbeat artists like Chris Brown or rap tracks by Eminem.
Pay Attention to Your Form
Seeing yourself lose form can eat away at your ability to perform. Checking your form every so often may help you keep your focus in check. Running a race is like performing a marathon dance routine. It's slower, but it is still dance. To keep your moves sharp, you need to keep it together and emphasize your steps. If you aren't maintaining proper form, unstack your feet, look at your shins, contact your heel with the floor first and run leggie in the sides with each step. If you still can't seem to keep your mind focused, it might be time to take a running poll to see how others can help.
